        <scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
            <head>Scope and Content </head>
            <p>A manuscript letter to an unidentified lord, possibly Lord Bute, discussing the Stamp
                Act passed by the British Parliament on March 22, 1765. The author describes the
                act, and the colonial response to it, as "the most important affair that has
                happened in more than half a century within the King's Dominions." He appeals to the
                lord for help raising "good out of evil". He suggests the colonies be allowed to
                raise taxes in their own manner. The letter is signed "Amor Patriae" and, based on
                the signature and address, is assumed to have been written by Thomas Crowley.
                Crowley used the same signature and address on a later publication. </p>
        </scopecontent>
